Aubrey de Grey, a 51-year-old biomedical theorist, believes that aging is a disease that can be cured, potentially allowing humans to live for hundreds or even thousands of years. His theories have gained support from wealthy Silicon Valley tech leaders, including PayPal's Peter Thiel and Google's co-founders, who have donated millions to de Grey's anti-aging research institute. While many academics dismiss his ideas as unrealistic, de Grey argues that emerging technologies will allow us to repair and replace damaged body parts at a cellular level, leading to dramatically extended lifespans.
Scientists have made a breakthrough in clean hydrogen power by developing a new material that can generate hydrogen from water more efficiently. The invention uses a newly designed molecular catalyst to split water in an electrolyser, making hydrogen production less reliant on fossil fuels and potentially more economical. This breakthrough could lead to more sustainable fuel production and better energy storage from renewable sources like wind and solar power.
A study by Stanford University researchers suggests that Fisher-Price alphabet magnets from the 1970s and 1980s may have influenced the color-letter associations of people with synaesthesia, a neurological condition where senses are involuntarily joined. The study found that at least 6% of participants, and up to 15% of those born in the decade after the toy's introduction, learned many of their color-letter matches from the Fisher-Price set. While the findings don't suggest that colorful toys cause synaesthesia, they indicate that external factors can influence the associations of people predisposed to the condition.
